\f1\fs24 \cf4 From the nine organizations that responded to the GA Voice LGBT organization survey, several key financial themes emerge:\
\'95 Individual donations make up a smaller percentage of budgets than you might think in a community as large as ours, coming in far below 50 percent for every organization except Savannah Pride (which has a small budget of only $50,000) and the StandUp Foundation (which benefited from a major anonymous donor in 2012).\
\'95 Federal and state grants support a large portion of some health agencies\'92 HIV work, but no local LGBT groups receive government funding.\
\'95 Corporate sponsorships are not common, either. Even Atlanta Pride, which gets chided from some activists for being \'93too corporate,\'94 gets less than half of its funding from corporate sponsorships \'97 and a miniscule 4.7 percent from individual donations.\
Survey participants included Atlanta Pride, Georgia Equality, The Health Initiative, Lost-N-Found Youth, Savannah Pride, the StandUP Foundation, AID Atlanta, Positive Impact and Someone Cares Atlanta.\
